mitre_attack_techniques.signature_description: Adversaries may use rootkits to hide the presence of programs, files, network connections, services, drivers, and other system components.
Adversaries may use bootkits to persist on systems.
Adversaries may attempt to hide artifacts associated with their behaviors to evade detection.
Adversaries may abuse utilities that allow for command execution to bypass security restrictions that limit the use of command-line interpreters.
Adversaries may maliciously modify components of a victim environment in order to hinder or disable defensive mechanisms.
Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools.
Adversaries may inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate privileges.

Adversaries may interact with the Windows Registry to hide configuration information within Registry keys, remove information as part of cleaning up, or as part of other techniques to aid in persistence and execution.
Adversaries may circumvent mechanisms designed to control elevate privileges to gain higher-level permissions.
Adversaries may delete or modify artifacts generated within systems to remove evidence of their presence or hinder defenses.
Adversaries may abuse Pre-OS Boot mechanisms as a way to establish persistence on a system.
**This technique has been deprecated.
Adversaries may modify and/or disable security tools to avoid possible detection of their malware/tools and activities.
Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit.
Adversaries may use hidden windows to conceal malicious activity from the plain sight of users.
Adversaries may create or modify references in user document templates to conceal malicious code or force authentication attempts.
Adversaries may set files and directories to be hidden to evade detection mechanisms.
An adversary may steal web application or service session cookies and use them to gain access to web applications or Internet services as an authenticated user without needing credentials.
Adversaries may configure system settings to automatically execute a program during system boot or logon to maintain persistence or gain higher-level privileges on compromised systems.
Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or referencing it with a Registry run key.
An adversary may attempt to get detailed information about the operating system and hardware, including version, patches, hotfixes, service packs, and architecture.
Adversaries may interact with the Windows Registry to gather information about the system, configuration, and installed software.
Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.
Adversaries may interact with the native OS application programming interface (API) to execute behaviors.
Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries.
Adversaries may abuse PowerShell commands and scripts for execution.
Adversaries may leverage the resources of co-opted systems in order to solve resource intensive problems, which may impact system and/or hosted service availability.
Adversaries may destroy data and files on specific systems or in large numbers on a network to interrupt availability to systems, services, and network resources.

T1014.description: Adversaries may use rootkits to hide the presence of programs, files, network connections, services, drivers, and other system components.

T1542.003.description: Adversaries may use bootkits to persist on systems.

T1564.description: Adversaries may attempt to hide artifacts associated with their behaviors to evade detection.

T1202.description: Adversaries may abuse utilities that allow for command execution to bypass security restrictions that limit the use of command-line interpreters.

T1562.description: Adversaries may maliciously modify components of a victim environment in order to hinder or disable defensive mechanisms.

T1036.description: Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools.
Uses an obfuscated file name to hide its real file extension (double extension)
Creates files inside the user directory
Creates files inside the system directory

T1055.description: Adversaries may inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate privileges.

T1112.description: Adversaries may interact with the Windows Registry to hide configuration information within Registry keys, remove information as part of cleaning up, or as part of other techniques to aid in persistence and execution.
Uses reg.exe to modify the Windows registry

T1548.description: Adversaries may circumvent mechanisms designed to control elevate privileges to gain higher-level permissions.

T1070.description: Adversaries may delete or modify artifacts generated within systems to remove evidence of their presence or hinder defenses.

T1542.description: Adversaries may abuse Pre-OS Boot mechanisms as a way to establish persistence on a system.

T1064.description: Found WSH timer for Javascript or VBS script (likely evasive script)

T1562.001.description: Adversaries may modify and/or disable security tools to avoid possible detection of their malware/tools and activities.
Creates guard pages, often used to prevent reverse engineering and debugging

T1027.description: Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit.
Uses an obfuscated file name to hide its real file extension (double extension)

T1564.003.description: Adversaries may use hidden windows to conceal malicious activity from the plain sight of users.

T1221.description: Adversaries may create or modify references in user document templates to conceal malicious code or force authentication attempts.

T1564.001.description: Adversaries may set files and directories to be hidden to evade detection mechanisms.

T1539.description: An adversary may steal web application or service session cookies and use them to gain access to web applications or Internet services as an authenticated user without needing credentials.

T1547.description: Adversaries may configure system settings to automatically execute a program during system boot or logon to maintain persistence or gain higher-level privileges on compromised systems.

T1547.001.description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or referencing it with a Registry run key.
Creates autostart registry keys with suspicious values

T1082.description: An adversary may attempt to get detailed information about the operating system and hardware, including version, patches, hotfixes, service packs, and architecture.
Queries the volume information (name, serial number etc) of a device
Checks the free space of harddrives
Uses systeminfo.exe to query system information

T1012.description: Adversaries may interact with the Windows Registry to gather information about the system, configuration, and installed software.

T1071.description: Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.

T1573.description: Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.

T1106.description: Adversaries may interact with the native OS application programming interface (API) to execute behaviors.

T1059.description: Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries.
Uses cmd line tools excessively to alter registry or file data
Very long cmdline option found, this is very uncommon (may be encrypted or packed)

T1059.001.description: Adversaries may abuse PowerShell commands and scripts for execution.

T1496.description: Adversaries may leverage the resources of co-opted systems in order to solve resource intensive problems, which may impact system and/or hosted service availability.

T1485.description: Adversaries may destroy data and files on specific systems or in large numbers on a network to interrupt availability to systems, services, and network resources.

T1497.description: May sleep (evasive loops) to hinder dynamic analysis

T1518.001.description: May try to detect the virtual machine to hinder analysis (VM artifact strings found in memory)

T1057.description: Windows shortcut file (LNK) starts blacklisted processes
Queries a list of all running processes

T1010.description: Sample monitors Window changes (e.g. starting applications), analyze the sample with the simulation cookbook
